programme.title: The "Off-Season" | Episode 1 | Who We Are
programme.desc: Welcome to the very first episode of The Bearded Buck's brand-new land management series called, The "Off-Season". This series will consist of short episodes dealing with the specifics of our land management tactics including everything from food plots, timber stand improvement, property development, trapping, and much more. We hope to show more of what it takes to set up a successful farm and what we do when we are not sitting in a tree stand hunting. Whether you hunt public ground, have permission to hunt private land, or own your own land, whether it's 5, 50, or 5000 acres, we hope you can find some useful information to help you become a better hunter and land manager. Also, we hope to show you that hunters really are about so much more than just a trigger pull. We are conservationists, land managers, and habitat creators. I want to emphasize that our way isn't necessarily the best way or the only way, it's just what has worked for us the last 20 years here at The Bearded Buck. We are truly passionate about conservation and land management, and we hope it shows through our new series The "Off-Season"!

programme.title: The "Off-Season" | Episode 2 | Soil Samples
programme.desc: In order to be a successful land manager that maintains a healthy wildlife population, your food plots need to be at the top of their game. The best way to achieve a productive food plot is to know exactly what type of soil your land has and what it needs to produce high quality forage. This is where soil samples come into play, arguably the most important step in the entire food plot process!

programme.title: The "Off-Season" | Episode 3 | Spring Food Plots
programme.desc: When the winter's snow has melted and the spring months roll around, every hunter gets excited about the anticipation of turkey season. While this is the case here on our farm, we are also anticipating the spring planting season. Fawns are developing, antlers are starting to form, and turkeys are about to lay eggs, making your spring food plot strategy vital to the quality of wildlife on your property!
